<h1 class="hero-h">How to hire <em style="font-family:'Instrument Serif',serif;font-style:italic;color:#00C853;">gym staff.</em></h1>
<p class="hero-sub">The 2026 hiring plan for fitness operators. What roles you actually need with AI agent infrastructure (fewer than you'd think), role design that doesn't overlap with what AI absorbs, interview process for the human roles that still matter, and compensation benchmarks by role and market.</p>
</div></div>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">The honest frame</span>
<h2 class="h2">Hire for what AI can't do</h2>
<p class="body">2026 gym hiring looks materially different from 2020 hiring. The roles AI agents reliably absorb — lead nurture, tour booking, no-show recovery, FAQ, churn signal outreach — were the "front desk + membership consultant" jobs operators used to hire 2-4 people for. AI now handles that work for $3K-$12K/year.</p>
<p class="body">What's left is the work AI doesn't do: instructor-led classes, personal training relationships, in-person greeting and access control, hands-on troubleshooting, community-building, conflict resolution, programming and curriculum decisions. <em>Hire deliberately for that work.</em> Don't replicate the old org chart and hope AI sits beside it; redesign the org chart around what humans uniquely do.</p>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">The lean staffing model</span>
<h2 class="h2">What a 2026 gym actually staffs</h2>
<h3 class="h3">Small boutique studio (100-300 active members)</h3>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Owner-operator (1):</strong> Strategy, hiring, key member relationships, instructor management, P&L</li>
<li><strong>Instructors (2-4 part-time or full-time):</strong> Class delivery, programming input, member coaching</li>
<li><strong>Studio coordinator (0.5-1 FTE):</strong> In-person greeting, cleaning oversight, member-experience details, AI agent escalation handoffs</li>
<li><strong>AI agent platform:</strong> Lead nurture, tour booking, no-show recovery, retention outreach, FAQ</li>
<li><strong>Total humans: 3-6.</strong> Pre-AI same gym would have run 6-9.</li>
</ul>
<h3 class="h3">CrossFit affiliate (80-200 members)</h3>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Owner-coach (1):</strong> Program design, leading 8-12 classes/week, member relationships</li>
<li><strong>Additional coaches (1-3):</strong> Class coverage, specialty programming</li>
<li><strong>Admin / coordinator (0.25-0.5 FTE):</strong> Cleaning oversight, supplies, in-person greeting at peak times</li>
<li><strong>AI agent platform.</strong></li>
<li><strong>Total humans: 2-5.</strong></li>
</ul>
<h3 class="h3">Mid-size group fitness studio (300-600 members)</h3>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Studio manager (1):</strong> Operations leadership, instructor scheduling, member experience</li>
<li><strong>Instructors (5-12 part-time):</strong> Wide class lineup coverage</li>
<li><strong>Coordinators (1-2 FTE):</strong> Cleaning, peak-hour greeting, special events</li>
<li><strong>AI agent platform.</strong></li>
<li><strong>Total humans: 7-15.</strong></li>
</ul>
<h3 class="h3">Full-service gym (1,500+ members)</h3>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>GM (1):</strong> Site leadership</li>
<li><strong>Department heads (2-4):</strong> Training, group fitness, sales/membership, ops</li>
<li><strong>Trainers (4-10):</strong> Personal training revenue + member coaching</li>
<li><strong>Group fitness instructors (8-20 part-time):</strong> Class lineup</li>
<li><strong>Front desk (2-4 FTE):</strong> Coverage during open hours; still meaningful at scale</li>
<li><strong>AI agent platform handles ~50% of what front desk used to do.</strong></li>
<li><strong>Total humans: 17-39.</strong> Still labor-heavy due to scale + in-person volume.</li>
</ul>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">Compensation benchmarks</span>
<h2 class="h2">What to pay in 2026</h2>
<div class="table-wrap"><table class="t"><thead><tr><th>Role</th><th>Tier-3 / suburban</th><th>Tier-2 metro</th><th>Tier-1 metro</th></tr></thead><tbody>
<tr><td>Studio coordinator / front desk (hourly)</td><td>$17-$20</td><td>$19-$23</td><td>$22-$28</td></tr>
<tr><td>Group fitness instructor (per class)</td><td>$35-$55</td><td>$45-$70</td><td>$60-$100</td></tr>
<tr><td>Personal trainer (employee, per session)</td><td>$30-$45</td><td>$35-$55</td><td>$45-$80</td></tr>
<tr><td>Personal trainer (contractor, % of session)</td><td>50-65%</td><td>50-65%</td><td>55-70%</td></tr>
<tr><td>CrossFit coach (per class)</td><td>$30-$45</td><td>$35-$55</td><td>$45-$75</td></tr>
<tr><td>Studio manager (boutique, annual)</td><td>$45K-$60K</td><td>$55K-$70K</td><td>$65K-$90K + bonus</td></tr>
<tr><td>GM (full-service, annual)</td><td>$55K-$70K + bonus</td><td>$65K-$85K + bonus</td><td>$80K-$120K + bonus</td></tr>
</tbody></table></div>
<p class="body"><strong>Add 22-30% for fully-loaded cost</strong> (payroll taxes, benefits, workers comp, training).</p>
<div class="callout"><p><strong>Overpay for the right hire.</strong> The cost of a poor instructor in a small studio is 5-15 member cancellations over six months — far more than the salary delta between an average instructor and an exceptional one.</p></div>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">Sourcing</span>
<h2 class="h2">Where to find the best candidates</h2>
<h3 class="h3">Instructors and coaches</h3>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Certification body alumni networks.</strong> NASM, NSCA, ACE, NCSF (personal training); CrossFit Level 1; AFAA (group fitness); RYT-200/500 (yoga). Direct outreach to recent grads in your trade area beats job-board postings.</li>
<li><strong>Your own members.</strong> Members who light up in class often want to teach. Most exceptional indie studio instructors are former members.</li>
<li><strong>Instructor-to-instructor referrals.</strong> Pay referral bonuses; the best instructors know other instructors.</li>
<li><strong>Local instructor Facebook groups + Slack communities.</strong> Active in most metros.</li>
</ul>
<h3 class="h3">Studio coordinators / front desk</h3>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Member referrals + retired members.</strong> People who already love the studio.</li>
<li><strong>Indeed / ZipRecruiter for volume.</strong> Screen heavily; expect 1-in-15 to be hire-able.</li>
<li><strong>Local college fitness/kinesiology programs.</strong> Especially for part-time evening coverage.</li>
</ul>
<h3 class="h3">GM / studio manager</h3>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Operator-network referrals.</strong> Ask other gym owners in adjacent markets who they'd hire if they could.</li>
<li><strong>Internal promotion.</strong> Best studio managers often started as instructors or coordinators.</li>
<li><strong>Targeted LinkedIn outreach.</strong> For experienced GM-level hires, direct outreach > posting.</li>
</ul>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">Interview process</span>
<h2 class="h2">A 4-step interview structure</h2>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>1. Screening call (15 min).</strong> Confirm certifications, schedule fit, compensation alignment. Cut anyone who's not a clear fit on basics before investing more time.</li>
<li><strong>2. Working interview / sample class (45-90 min).</strong> For instructors and coaches — teach a real class to a small group of staff or members. Watch the room.</li>
<li><strong>3. Owner conversation (45 min).</strong> Values, communication style, why this gym specifically. Look for genuine curiosity about the studio's members, not just "I need a job."</li>
<li><strong>4. Reference checks (2 minimum).</strong> Ask former employers about reliability, member feedback, and growth trajectory. Trust this signal — chronic issues recur.</li>
</ul>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">Common mistakes</span>
<h2 class="h2">Five hiring mistakes that hurt member experience</h2>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>1. Hiring for the wrong role.</strong> Adding "front desk" headcount when AI already absorbs that work. Hire for the human work instead.</li>
<li><strong>2. Underpaying instructors.</strong> The instructor is the product at most boutique studios. A $5/class compensation delta vs market is the cheapest mistake you can make.</li>
<li><strong>3. Hiring too fast in year one.</strong> Run lean while AI absorbs the admin work and your model gets validated. Add humans deliberately based on real demand signals.</li>
<li><strong>4. No working interview for instructors.</strong> Resumes lie; live classes don't. Always do a sample class.</li>
<li><strong>5. Skipping reference checks.</strong> 20 minutes of reference calls prevents 6 months of pain.</li>
</ul>
</div></section>

